        <div class="col-md-6">
        <h6>Topic A<br/>Foreign Military Bases</h6>
        <p>
            The establishment of foreign military bases is a key matter to understand the distribution of power in spheres of influence throughout the world. Oversea bases are the first mechanism of a mass network which works to maintain the control exercised by great powers, becoming the infrastructure for wars.
        </p>
        <p>
            The use of military power to access another country’s soil is not a modern practice. It dates to the old Greece and its city-states (Harvaky 1989). In the 15th century, in the context of the maritime empires’ expansion and their dispute for discovered territories, basing access became crucial to defend new lands and to serve as trading posts, securing vital interests of great powers such as the Iberian Monarchies and the British Empire (Harvaky 1989). Nevertheless, it was from the 20th century onwards, with the two Great Wars and the consequently ascension of the USA and the USSR as superpowers, that the establishment of oversea military bases has assumed the configuration we are known to today.
        </p>
        <p>
            Foreign military bases became the most important apparatus of organizations as NATO and European Union. The use of this tool when it is related to interventions is currently justified by great powers as a protective measure in territories in conflict or in territories where governments are considered dangerous for its own population (Zeijden 2009). However, it is possible to draw a link between the foreign presence abroad and the possibility of overthrowing governments on the battle ground.
        </p>
        <p>
            Since the 9/11 episode, the establishment of oversea military posts has increased and turned into a key dimension of US foreign policy against the War on Terror. According to the Defense Department’s annual “Base Structure Report”, from 2013, the US have about 600 military installations abroad, distributed over allied countries as United Kingdom, Israel and Japan and also over non-partners countries, such as Cuba and Afghanistan. According to Wilbert van der Zeijden (2009), from the Transnational Institute,
        </p>
        <p class="citation"><em>
            (…) many of the 300 overseas military interventions and invasions of the US in the past century, like Korean War, Vietnam War and Gulf War, were only possible because the US had well-positioned military facilities to launch and support these military operations.
        </em></p>
        <p>
            The current developments regarding Ukraine, Russia and Crimea reinforce the strategic importance of foreign military bases. Through the Agreement between the Russian Federation and Ukraine on the Status and Conditions of the Russian Federation Black Sea Fleet’s Stay on Ukrainian Territory, Russia has the authority to locate troops on its bases in Crimea, and to move them between those bases and Russian territory (Posner 2014). However, such presence could represent a threat to Ukraine’s sovereignty in case of conflicts: the recent events exemplify these worries as well as the strategic role of maintaining overseas bases. Sebastopol, the city where Russian naval forces were historically located with Ukraine’s permissions is now declared a legitimate Russian territory, reinforcing questions about the establishment of foreign military bases.
        </p>
        <p>
            Besides security issues, another quarrel that must be tackled related to the establishment of military bases abroad is the concept of sovereignty. The Status of Force Agreement (SOFA) is the main accord responsible for regulating the presence of oversea military bases. It is signed by a host country and a foreign nation and provides the rights and the privileges of foreign military people who turn exempt from local laws (Mason 2012). However, this agreement and the continued presence of foreign bases itself are considered by many as a violation of sovereignty, being just a mechanism to project power over strategic regions.
        </p>
        <p>
            Foreign military resources installed in another’s soil are usually linked to air stations, navy bases or army bases. Some of these military posts are test ranges for new weaponry or are related to intelligence programs, as Echelon, being important signal receivers. Through these facilities, overseabases are consolidated into great powers’ foreign policy, being an integral part in many regional conflicts or an economic and political support to allied governments (Zeijden 2009).
        </p>
        <p>
            Therefore, the establishment of foreign military bases is a complex and paradoxical issue which involves many concepts and interests. Are the great powers really protecting other countries? From who are they supposed to be defending their allies from? This way, we invite all DISEC delegates to join us and discuss this important matter in order to answer these questions and find the best solution for this controversial practice.
        </p>
        <p class="references">
            References: Harvaky, Robert. 1989. Bases Abroad: The Global Foreign Military Presence. Oxford: Oxford University Press.
            | Manson, Chuck. 2012. “Status of Force Agreement (SOFA): What is it and How Has It Been Utilized?”. Congressional Research Service. Accessed January 19, 2014. Available in: https://www.fas.org/sgp/crs/natsec/RL34531.pdf.
            | Posner, E. “The 1997 Black Sea Fleet Agreement between Russia and Ukraine”. Accessed April 22, 2014. http://ericposner.com/the-1997-black-sea-fleet-agreement-between-russia-and-ukraine.
            | Zeijden, Wilbert. 2009. Foreign Military Bases and the Global Campaign to close them. Accessed July 21, 2009. Available in: http://www.tni.org/primer/foreign-military-bases-and-global-campaign-close-them.
        </p>
